<TEXT>
organizers of a rodeo for homosexuals on 
friday accused officials of the university of nevadareno officials 
of bowing to public pressure and using a contract dispute to cancel 
the contest 
in august the universitys lawlor events center canceled the 
contract to rent out its stadium oct 2123 for the international 
championship gay rodeo in which top riders from regional gay 
rodeos compete 
i think it is just an excuse on the part of lawlor to prevent 
these types of events from coming to the facility attorney rod 
sumpter told a washoe district court judge 
don klasic general counsel for the university and lawlor 
denied the charge telling the judge it has always been a 
contract action this is not a civil rights action 
on sept 1 the international gay rodeo and the silver state gay 
rodeo associations sued unr which oversees the events center on 
its campus 
the associations are seeking an injuction from judge william 
forman to force lawlor to rent its stadium for the gay rodeo which 
has been advertised for several months throughout the world 
forman said he would rule on the injuction monday 
klasic told the court the contract was cancelled by lawlor after 
aug 15 when the gay organization failed to come up with 9000 in 
prepayments to cover expenses for security parking cleanup and 
other operation costs 
he said lawlor became concerned about the organizations ability 
to pay expenses so a prepayment schedule was orally agreed to in 
june 
les krambeal president of the international association said 
he only agreed to the demands because he feared lawlor otherwise 
would cancel the event his organization paid 2263 in prepayments 
before running out of money 
during initial contract talks in october 1987 and when the 
document was signed in february 1988 krambeal said he was told 
expenses would not be due until oct 23 
sumpter said the written contract did not call for any 
prepayments instead it only required that 7300 be paid up front 
to rent out the stadium which was done he said 
sumpter said lawlor used the financial concern as a way to cause 
the association to violate its contract because of negative 
complaints from area residents who protested similar events held in 
the late 1970s and early 1980s 
the prepayment plan was decided only after news leaked that a 
gay rodeo was returning to reno and two local business groups told 
lawlor officials that previous gay rodeo organizations didnt pay 
all their bills he said 
</TEXT>
