<TEXT>
former navy secretary john lehman says the 
changes during his controversial tenure didnt lead to the current 
pentagon investigation of bribery in navy contracts 
i am very proud of the achievements made in rebuilding the 
navy during my tenure i do not believe the changes that led to 
that success made the system by its nature more susceptible to 
waste fraud and abuse he said friday 
lehmans appearance before the house armed services committee 
was his first major public comment since the ongoing investigation 
became public three months ago 
the investigation concerns allegations of bribes from 
consultants many of them former pentagon employees to current 
defense department employees to obtain inside information about 
contracts those details could be crucial to winning multimillion 
dollar contracts no charges have yet been filed 
a key figure of the investigation is melvyn paisley the former 
assistant navy secretary for research and engineering and a close 
associate of lehman during their navy tenure 
paisley resigned and became a highpriced consultant shortly 
after lehman quit to take a wall street job in april 1987 
lehman was a controversial figure during his sixyear tenure 
often clashing with lawmakers and other critics of reagans naval 
buildup that buildup was the key component of reagans program of 
large increases in the pentagon budget 
lehman didnt talk about specifics of the investigation and 
committee members didnt seek those details because they didnt 
want to harm the probe but he noted the navy has more consultants 
than the other services chiefly because the service has fewer 
officers some navy tasks are performed by consultants that in the 
army and air force would be done by officers he said 
consultants are essential but we do have too many he 
added the navy could substantially reduce its reliance on 
consultants 
i was never comfortable with the dependence on consultants 
lehman said adding that his efforts to reduce that dependence were 
thwarted by unidentified bureaucrats 
lehman did endorse a pair of reforms proposed after the 
investigation became public one would require consultants to 
register and the other would direct them to disclose all their 
contracts to prevent conflicts of interest 
lehman strongly defended his running of the navy disputing 
critics who have said the changes he ordered may have fostered a 
climate which led to the investigation those changes include more 
centralized management and elimination of some layers of 
bureaucracy 
with regard to strong centralized policymaking and 
decentralized execution i see no way that either principle 
increases the opportunity for waste fraud and abuse he said 
overall said lehman the pentagon should be reorganized to give 
much more authority for daily decisions to lowerlevel personnel 
rather than top officials he opposed the creation of a single 
purchasing czar a change proposed by some lawmakers 
he proposed that the secretary of defense simply make policy 
and turn all other major decisions over to the three services 
the staff also should be reduced by half he said 
</TEXT>
