<TEXT>
a steady rain fell saturday as a small 
wagon train departed from red clay state historical park for 
tahlequah okla to commemorate the 150th anniversary of the 
infamous trail of tears 
its fitting observed ray morris the coordinator of the 
project from what ive read the first bunch of cherokees were 
forced to leave on a day much like this one 
morris of golconda ill drove one of the six covered wagons 
that will make the 1000mile journey scheduled to end in early 
december participants hope to call attention to the federal 
governments forced removal of the cherokees from their eastern 
homelands in 1838 
i think the blackest chapter of our nations history began 
with the indian removal act of 1830 and culminated with the 
relocation of the cherokees in 1838 morris said 
the government called it a treaty but what it really amounted 
to was at gunpoint they were made 
to leave their homes and walk to oklahoma so the white settlers 
could have their land 
according to historical accounts of the trek the first group of 
cherokees numbering about 1000 departed oct 1 1838 from red 
clay their last tribal council ground in the east they were 
accompanied by federal troops and state militia in all 13 groups 
of indians made the trek 
about 4000 of the indians or more than onethird of those 
who started out from tennessee in the fall of 1838 died along the 
way morris said yet there are only two marked graves in 
hopkinsville ky along the entire route of the trail of tears 
its a page of our history thats largely been ignored 
the wagons that left red clay on saturday were pulled by four 
mule teams and two teams of horses a halfdozen riders on 
horseback also joined the first leg of the trek 
among the riders was ricky todd a farmer from woodbury tenn 
who said he first heard of the trail of tears as a little boy when 
he saw it mentioned on a plaque woodbury was one of the towns the 
indians went through 
todd is the projects tennessee coordinator 
this is an educational project and wed like for people to 
come out and walk or ride with us for a while he said in my 
town i know the schoolchildren will be coming down to see the 
wagon train and learn more about what happened on the trail of 
tears 
we want them to know that the cherokees werent savages in 
loincloths that they were a civilized people whose land was stolen 
by the white man 
morris said the wagons represent each of the six states the 
cherokees went through on their way to oklahoma 
the cherokees followed a circuitous route through tennessee 
kentucky illinois missouri arkansas and oklahoma a route that 
later would be known as the trail of tears he said were 
going to stay as close to that route as is possible 
