<TEXT>
when the stock market acts like a bull many 
investors concentrate on capital appreciation and all but forget 
dividends 
the reason why is hardly complex since almost anyone is likely 
to be attracted to a oneday leap of 1 a share vs a dividend that 
might amount to less than that for an entire year 
but when the market stalls as it seems now to be doing 
interest in dividends returns newsletter writers tout 
highdividend stocks and brokers offer clients their lists of 
prospects for dividend increases 
when the talk is about dividends you know the spirit of the 
marketplace has changed that it has become calmer more realistic 
more attuned to economic conditions and most likely healthier 
smart investors however never lose interest in dividend 
yields even when others are talking about huge oneday profits and 
the promoters are talking about a new era and new levels of 
prosperity 
the dividend collectors however know that over the long run 
they sometimes can make more in dividends a bit at a time than 
others might make and lose in sharply fluctuating prices 
investment information services one of the newbreed market 
researchers who rely on cold hard provable data in contrast to 
the emotions promotions and shenanigans that predominated from 
1982 to 1987 offers this evidence 
over the past 38 years the total return on the standard amp 
poors 500stock index has averaged 114 percent of this 46 
percent came from dividends the rest from capital appreciation 
reinvestment of dividends over a long period of time can boost 
an investors wealth enormously little dividends become big sums 
when compounded that is when dividends reinvested earn dividends 
themselves 
if you had invested 1000 in the sampp beginning in 1926 and 
withdrawn all dividends during that time your investment would 
have been worth 19366 by the end of 1987 
but had you reinvested all the dividend payments so that they 
in turn could earn dividends your portfolio during the same time 
would have grown to 347956 
such evidence is not new but it still arrives with a shock on 
the current market scene having been scorned for years by a public 
that believed a stock puchased in the morning should show a gain by 
afternoon 
dividends cannot do that since seldom are they offered more 
than once in three months moreover you must pay taxes on 
dividends whereas you can defer any tax on capital gains until you 
sell 
there are other reasons too why dividends fall out of favor 
during bull markets chief of them being the notion that 
dividendpaying companies are too plodding too conservative too 
slowgrowing 
but when the marketplace returns to its senses as it probably 
has now the beauty of dividends returns to its proper place in 
investment philosophies 
</TEXT>
