<TEXT>
oil futures prices declined in moderate trading 
as the market shifted its attention from hurricane gilbert to the 
oversupply of oil around the world 
on the new york mercantile exchange the october contract for 
west texas intermediate the benchmark grade of us crude settled 
33 cents lower at 1457 a 42gallon barrel friday compared with 
thursdays closing price of 1490 a barrel other contract months 
also settled lower 
wholesale unleaded gasoline for october delivery closed down 
141 cents at 4422 cents a gallon compared with 4563 cents a 
gallon on thursday the contract rose more than 3 cents on 
wednesday on fears of a hurricaneinduced gasoline shortage 
the october wholesale heating oil contract fell 133 cents a 
gallon to close at 4137 cents a gallon compared with 4270 cents 
on thursday 
analysts said the market opened lower and traded in a narrow 
range friday before weakening at the end of the day along with the 
prospects of a disruption in domestic gasoline and crude oil 
supplies in the gulf of mexico 
the market had rallied earlier in the week on reports the 
hurricane was approaching the us coastline near texas and 
louisiana and that many us refineries had ceased operations 
but by thursday analysts said the focus shifted to production 
concerns as threats of a hurricane doing serious damage dissipated 
by friday companies which had evacuated workers from oil platforms 
announced they were resuming operations 
once the hurricane is off the front pages the market will be 
back to looking at the supply and demand situation and i dont 
think that looks constructive said william byers an analyst 
with bear stearns amp co 
reports this week indicated the 13member organization of 
petroleum exporting countries had reduced its production last 
month from 20 million barrels a day to below 19 million but still 
more than the market can absorb according to analysts 
that preceded an announcement that the cartels price monitoring 
committee would meet sept 25 and 26 suggesting that opec might be 
serious about setting production limits that would strengthen world 
oil prices 
but on thursday iraqis oil minister slowed the markets upward 
momentum by announcing his country would not lower its oil output 
and might raise its production instead 
that dampens any optimism about what could come out of an opec 
meeting said john azarow an analyst with shearson lehman hutton 
inc 
iraq has refused to abide by its opecassigned quota of 15 
million barrels a day and is reported to be producing about 27 
million barrels a day some observers hoped that after a recent 
ceasefire in its 8yearold war with iran iraq would join with 
other opec nations in restraining production 
