<TEXT>
investors who had second thoughts after they bought gold as a 
hedge against inflation have pushed the price of the precious metal 
lower 
gold prices continued to tumble friday shedding nearly 7 a 
troy ounce the plunge brought the twoday decline in gold prices 
to roughly 18 an ounce and left gold at its lowest point since 
march 1987 
republic national bank in new york quoted gold bullion at 
41175 a troy ounce as of 4 pm edt 
unlike stocks and bonds gold does not provide dividends its 
main merit is it keeps its value when paper investments are eroded 
by inflation but inflation has been lower than gold investors had 
expected 
these people are disappointed and shocked and adding fuel to 
the fire said steven pepper vice president and bullion dealer 
at republic national bank the more selling that comes in the 
more these people are in a panic 
in other markets friday stocks gained some ground and the dow 
jones average of 30 industrials rose 587 to 209815 the dollar 
was mixed and bonds drifted slightly lower in sluggish trading 
the government said friday business inventories rose in july at 
the slowest rate in 11 months an indication sales were strong 
enough to keep goods from piling up on the shelves 
the commerce department said inventories rose 03 percent the 
smallest rise since one of 02 percent in august 1987 
economists believe businesses have been intentionally adding to 
their inventories in a small way to have a buffer for continued 
strong sales 
business sales fell 02 percent in july but the decline was not 
considered worrisome because it followed a strong 14 percent jump 
in june 
when you put june and july together sales are still growing 
strongly said james annable chief economist of first national 
bank of chicago 
